  "prompt": "Why is Manaphy annoying in Pokemon ranger and the temple of the sea?",
  "response": "In \"Pok\u00e9mon Ranger and the Temple of the Sea,\" Manaphy, while being an endearing and integral character, can be perceived as annoying by some viewers primarily due to its behavior and the challenges it presents to the protagonists. Here are a few reasons why:\n\n1. **Dependency**: Manaphy is depicted as a baby Pok\u00e9mon, which means it requires constant care and attention. This dependency can lead to situations where it unintentionally causes trouble or puts itself in danger, requiring the main characters to intervene repeatedly.\n\n2. **Communication Issues**: As a mythical Pok\u00e9mon, Manaphy cannot communicate directly with humans except through emotions and simple actions. This can create misunderstandings or complicate situations, making it frustrating for both the characters in the film and the audience.\n\n3. **Attracting Trouble**: Manaphy's rarity and significance attract the attention of villains who seek to capture it for their own purposes. This creates continuous tension and conflict throughout the movie, as the protagonists must protect Manaphy from these threats.\n\n4. **Pull of the Sea**: Throughout the movie, Manaphy is instinctively drawn toward the sea and the Temple of the Sea, which can lead to challenging scenarios for the human characters who are trying to keep it safe and fulfill its destiny.\n\nThese elements are designed to add both depth and conflict to the story, driving the plot forward and highlighting themes of friendship and responsibility, even if they can be occasionally perceived as annoying.",
